han twice as many a year\nearlier. Examiners with proper\ntraining and experience still\nare needed.\nMore college graduates are\nshowing interest in this type of\nwork and are majoring in ac\ncounting and business adminis\ntration to prepare for it.\nFoud Brokers to Hold\nFinal Dinnrr Meeting\nThe Washington Food Brok\ners Association will hold us\nfinal dinner meeting of the sea- j\nson at Kenwood Country Club\nMonday night.\nExecutives of Safeway Stores,,\nheaded by Division Manager\nEdgar Balsliaw. will be guests'\nof the association and John\nKluge; head of the food brok\nerage firm bearing his name,\nand association president, will\npreside.\nArea Printers Listed\nAmong Top in Nation\nFive area men were listed\namong the 75 top leaders in\nthe commercial printing in\ndustry of the Nation in the cur\nrent issue of the Inland\nPrinter. national trade\nmagazine.\nThey included: Peter Becker,\nJr\u201e owner of Arrow Service;\nWillard E. Brown, assistant vice\npresident. Judd and Detweiler,\nInc.: Otis H. Johnson, presi\ndent. Rufus H. Darby Printing\nCo.: Walter P. McArdle. presi\ndent, McArdle Printing Co.; j\nLeslie C. Shomo. vice president, l\nNational Publishing Co.\nThree Winners Chosen\nIn Speech Contest\nThree winners were chosen in\nthe semi-finals of the annual\n5-minute speech contest of\nWashington Chapter, American\nInstitute of Banking, at the\nBurlington Hotel. Tuesday\nnight.\nThey are: Ray P. Qoetz. First\nFederal Savings and Loan As\nsociation of Washington: Karl\nE Penner, District Building As\nsociation. and Jerry D. Whit\nlock. Home Federal Savings and\nLoan Association.\nThe finalists will compete at\nchapter graduation exercises\nJune 21 and the winner will\nrepresent Washington in the\nnational contest in San Fran\ncisco next November.\nGarfinckel Board Votei\nQuarterly Dividends\nDirectors of Julius Garfinckel\nSc Co. yesterday declared regu\nlar quarterly dividends of 281*\ni cents a share on the 4*4 per\ncent convertible preferred stock\nand 40 cents a share on com-j\nmon stock.\nBoth dividends will be paid\ni June 30 to stockholders of\ni record June 13.\ni\nMetro. Inr., Announces\n1 Regular Distributions\nDirectors of Metro. Inc., de\ni dared regular quarterly divi\ni dends of 17*i cents a share on\npreferred stock and 15 cents a\nshare on common stock.\nBoth dividends will be paid\ni June 27 to stockholders of\nrecord June 13.\nGELICO Votes\nStock Melon,\nMore Cash\nDirector! of Government Em\nployee* Life Insurance Co. yea\nterday declared a (look divi\ndend of 3>a per cent or 5.279\nsharea and tncreaaed the an\nnual cash dividend rate to 40\ncenla a share from 30 cents\npaid prevloualy. President L. A.\nDavidson announced.\nO ELI CO paid a 3 per cent\nstock dividend last year and\nsemiannual cash dividends\ntotaling 30 cents. It paid a\n2'j per cent stock dividend and\ncash dividends totalinc 20 cents\nin 1956.\nThe stock dividend will be\npaid June 25 to holders of\nrecord June 6 at the rate of\none share for each 40 shares\nheld. It is Intended to capitalize\nthe undistributed portion of\n1957 earnings, Mr. Davidson\nsaid.\nTo put the higher cash rate\nInto effect, directors declared\na .semiannual cash dividend of\n20 cents a share, payable June\n30 to holders of record June\n16.\nThe stock dividend will re\nsult in a fraction of a share\nfor some holders. Stock under\nlying all fractions will be sold\nat the market and proceeds will\nbe distributed ratably.\nStock certificates and checks\nrepresenting fractional inter\nests in payment of the stock\ndividend will be forwarded to\nholders by the transfer agent.\nRiggs National Bank. Checks\nfor the cash dividend will go\nout June 30.\nC&P Allots\nMore Funds\nChesapeake Sc Potomac Tele\nphone Co. of Baltimore City\nwill spend $2,253,000 for ex\npansion of facilities in various\ncities.\nAround $1,764,000 will be\nused to replace cable, poles and\noutside wire lines damaged by\nthe snow and sleet storm in\nMarch. This will be In addition\nto $1 million already alloted for\nthis purpose.\nThe total includes $49,000 for\na building addition and dial\nexpansion at Walkersville,\n$145,000 for Annapolis expan\nsion. SIOI,OOO for cable to new\nHyattsville developments. *92,-\n000 for Gaithersburg cable and\n*3l 000 for expansion in the\nPeppermill Village section of\nSuitland.\nV\\\\\nNATIONAI^IONORS ~,,i\nPete Bozick, proprietor of\nMarlow Liquors in Mar\nlow Heights, Md., was\nnamed Liquor Dealer of\n1957 among some 60.000\npackage liquor dealers of\nthe country by the Ed\nGibbs News Letter. Mr.\nBozick\u2019s stor was the first\nself-service liquor store\nin this area He received\nthe award yesterday\nStar Staff Photo.\nVISIT BEAUTIFUL\nfait***\n.x...\n4/\nM wr\u00abf MH TOMOW?OW\nA ..JUST INTIMim THE HOLIOAV\nf\\M THeMMLi\nfWAMv of \"fUN iNgjjje suh'?;\nf V TYSON'* I\ncorner 1 Falls X\nesMAiaaiiur mu.ii/* W CHILDREN\n0 WVINGr UHK KA4\neSM> NEW, MO9EKN BATH HOUSE*\n\u2022SNACK BAK*HORSEBACK RlWNfr* P/CNIC/NG-*\nMAWV&EM\u00a3NT RESERVES RIGHT TO REFUSE ADMITTANCE TO ANYONE\nw -tbJt. ts\nx I ,jV\njM\nWILLIAM C. CREEKMORE\nBank Auditors\nWill Be Headed\nBy Creekmore\nWilliam C. Creekmore. audi\ntor of the National Savings ti\nTrust Co., was elected chair\nman of the Auditors Section of\nthe District Bankers Associa\ntion at the Shoreham Hotel last\nnight.\nHe succeeds Robert E. Kend\nrick of the Bank of Commerce.\nMr. Creekmore has been as\nsociated with National Savings\nsince 1941 and became auditor\nin 1953. He is a Marine veteran\nof World War 11. has a degree\nfrom Benjamin Franklin Uni\nversity and is a graduate of the\nSchool for Bank Auditors and\nControllers at the University of\nWisconsin.\nOther new officers of the sec\ntion are Raymond E. Sparks.\nLincoln National, vice chair\nman; Chester B. Sellner. Amer\nican Security, secretary, and\nDavid P. Griffin. Anacostia\nNational, treasurer.\nIn addition to the officers. F.\nStewart Geigan of the National\nBank of Washington. Raymond\nEutsler of the City Bank and\nMr. Kendrick will serve on the\nexecutive council.\nv r\nSTARGAZING\nBy FRANCIS P. DOUGLAS\nFAST SHIP TO EUROPE\u2014If\nvou put off that trip to Europe\nlong enough you may be ablej\nj to make it in a little more than\ntwo days at twice the speed of\ntoday's fastest liner, the United\nStates.\nThe United States' operating\nspeed is 31 knots, or 35.5 mile*\nper hour. Your ship of the fu\nture may do it at 70 miles per\nhour.\nThe Maritime Administra\ntion is carrying on a research\n1 and development program The\nresearch work on the vessel of\nthe future is not being done by\na ship-building company or a\nnaval architect but by the\nGrumman Aircraft Engineer- 1\ning Corp.\nWhat is being studied is a\nhydrofoil craft. The hydrofoil;\nwould have a shape similar to\nI that of an airplane wing. But\nIt would be much smaller be\ncause it would operate in the\ndenser medium of water.\nThe vessel would be sup\nported on stilt-like legs above\nthe hydrofoil Prooelled through\nthe water at sufficient speed,\nthe hydrofoil would lift the\nvessel out of the water It is re\nported that a large hydrofoil\nwould not be affected in a\nmoderate sea and only slightly\naffected in heavy seas. The;\npower may come from a nu\nclear power reactor.\nSmall hydrofoil vessels al\nready are In operation. Experi\nmental data indicate that such\na craft could be built of 120\ntons, to carry 300 passengers at\nhigh speeds and at less power\nand cost per passenger than for\na conventional ship.\nCargo Submarines, Too\u2014\niThe hydrofoil vessel is not the\nwhole research story. Also\nbeing studied is a cargo sub-\nmarine. Significantly, the com- i\npanies engaged in this project\nare the Electric Boat Division\nof General Dynamics Corp.\nand the Aerojet-General Corp.\nElectric Boat is completing\nthe Skipjack, the Navy's i\nspeediest atomic-powered sub- j\nVast Metro\nD.C. Area Seen\nBy Realtors\nBEDFORD SPRINOS. Pa\nMay 29 <SpecialA vast met\nropolitan area encompassing\nWashington and Baltimore la\nnot too far in the future, a key\nnoter declared at the opening\nof the Washington Real Estate\nBoard's fourth annual conven\ntion here today.\nThe keynoter. President Ed\nward J. Kyle said rapid devel\nopment of both cities calls for\nsteps to prepare for an \"era of\nmetropolitan government.\"\nSuch major community serv\nices as transportation, police\nand fire protection, water sup\nply, schools and hospitals must\nASSOCIATE EDITOR\nDonald W. Dresden, for\nmer public relations\nexecutive, has been named\nassociate editor of Chang\ning Times, the Klplinger\nmagazine. A resident of\nGeorgetown, hid articles\nhave appeared in the Sat\nurday Evening Post, Na\ntional Geographic and\nother magazines.\nmarine which, it is believed,\nwill have an underwater speed\nof 50 miles an hour. Areojet-\nGeneral has experience in jet\npropulsion in rockets and\nhighspeed underwater bodies.\nResearch has indicated that\na commercial submarine might\nbe built to make better than\n65 miles per hour.\nThere is also reported the\nprospect that such a submarine\ncould make an ocean crossing\nunder automatic operation,\navoiding other vessels or ob\nstruction. It would require\nmanning only when leaving or\narriving at a harbor.\nThere is the question of size.\nThe British are reported work\ning on an underwater commer\ncial tanker with 80,000 tons\ncapacity.\nIs all this fantastic? Cer\ntainly. But not as fantastic as\nman-made earth satellites.\nCHICAGO\nLIVESTOCK\nCHICAGO, Mav 2J> </f>. 'UBDA>\nHogs S.OUU; moderately active; steady\nto weak on butchers: sows slow *.'eady\nto 25 lower on weights under 400 lbs:\nmore outlet for weUhts over 400 lbs:\nfheae fully 25 lower: closed 25 to\n1 lower: butchers under 2.*10 lbs very\nscarce: 2-;j 190*280 lb butchers 22 75-\nj 23.16; several lotv 1-2 195-2241 lbs\n123.25-2.3.50; small volume 1* these,\nweights 2.1.60-23.75: around HO head\nat 28.75; 2-8 285-200 lbs 22.25-22.75; j\nfew 1-2 285-240 lbs to 82.00: 2-8\n270-290 lbs 2